#{\footnote 20894}
#{\footnote 20900}
${\footnote Texture Magnification Filter}
+{\footnote 1}
K{\footnote Texture Magnification Filter;Object Texture Magnification Filter;}
\pard \plain \brdrb \cf12 \fs24 \b
\{bmc IDF20894.bmp\} Texture Magnification Filter, \{bmc IDF20900.bmp\} Object Texture Magnification Filter\par
\pard \plain \cf0 \fs20
{\uldb Settings}{\v 20796}, {\uldb Textures}{\v 20915}\par
\par
The \b \i texture magnification filter \i0 \b0 element is a logic switch. If it is on, then the texels (i.e. texture pixels) are interpolated in a linear way, when the texture gets magnified. Thus the texture is smoothed during the magnification. If the switch is off, then the nearest pixel is used when drawing the magnified texture. Thus sharp transitions between texels are visible on the texture being drawn. It is recommended to switch off the texture filtration when using a software driver, because the software filtration slows down the rendering process considerably.\par
\par
The texture magnification filter can be switched off in any object and texture stage separately by the \b \i object texture magnification filter \i0 \b0 command (for an {\uldb active object}{\v 20810} and an {\uldb active stage}{\v 20916}). If the \b \i texture magnification filter \i0 \b0 switch is off, then the texture magnification filter is off in all objects, independently of the position of the switches for texture magnification filter of the individual objects. The default setting of all switches is ON.\par
\page

#{\footnote 20872}
#{\footnote 20899}
${\footnote Texture Minification Filter}
+{\footnote 1}
K{\footnote Texture Minification Filter;Object Texture Minification Filter;}
\pard \plain \brdrb \cf12 \fs24 \b
\{bmc IDF20872.bmp\} Texture Minification Filter, \{bmc IDF20899.bmp\} Object Texture Minification Filter\par
\pard \plain \cf0 \fs20
{\uldb Settings}{\v 20796}, {\uldb Textures}{\v 20915}\par
\par
The \b \i texture minification filter \i0 \b0 element is a logic switch. If it is on, then the texels (i.e. texture pixels) are interpolated in a linear way, when the texture gets minified. Thus the texture is smoothed during the minification. If the switch is off, then the nearest pixel is used when drawing the minified texture. Thus sharp transitions between texels are visible on the texture being drawn. It is recommended to switch off the texture filtration when using a software driver, because the software filtration slows down the rendering process considerably.\par
\par
If the {\uldb faraway texture filter}{\v 20895} switch is on, then the individual stages of the faraway textures are interpolated when the minified texture switch is on. When the minified texture switch is off the nearest stage of the faraway texture is used (the texture refining changes abruptly when the distance is changed).\par
\par
The texture minification filter can be switched off in any object and texture stage separately by the \b \i object texture minification filter \i0 \b0 command (for an {\uldb active object}{\v 20810} and an {\uldb active stage}{\v 20916}). If the \b \i texture minification filter \i0 \b0 switch is off, then the texture minification filter is off in all objects, independently on the position of the switches for texture minification filter of the individual objects. The default setting of all switches is ON.\par
\page

#{\footnote 20895}
#{\footnote 20901}
${\footnote Faraway Texture Filter}
+{\footnote 1}
K{\footnote Faraway Texture Filter;Object Faraway Texture Filter;Mipmap;}
\pard \plain \brdrb \cf12 \fs24 \b
\{bmc IDF20895.bmp\} Faraway Texture Filter, \{bmc IDF20901.bmp\} Object Faraway Texture Filter\par
\pard \plain \cf0 \fs20
{\uldb Settings}{\v 20796}, {\uldb Textures}{\v 20915}\par
\par
The \b \i faraway texture filter \i0 \b0 is a logic switch. If it is on, minified textures (called mipmaps) are used in faraway objects. Thus it is possible to attain a more natural appearance in faraway objects (defocusing). If the switch is off, the basic non-minified texture is used (The faraway objects' surface "granulates").\par
\par
The manner of the faraway texture filter is influenced by the position of the {\uldb texture minification filter}{\v 20872} switch. If the texture minification switch is on, linear interpolation between two nearest minified textures made use of. If the texture minification switch is off, then the nearest minified texture is brought to bear (When changing the distance, the blurring of the faraway textures changes abruptly).\par
\par
The faraway texture filter can be switched in any object and texture stage separately by the \b \i object faraway texture filter \i0 \b0 command (for an {\uldb active object}{\v 20810} and an {\uldb active stage}{\v 20916}). If the \b \i faraway texture filter \i0 \b0 switch is off, the faraway texture filter is off in any object, independently of the position of the object faraway texture filter switches of the individual objects. The default setting of all switches is ON.\par
\par
The manner of the faraway texture filter can be further specified by means of the {\uldb number of faraway textures}{\v 20929} and {\uldb blurring of faraway textures}{\v 20925} elements.\par
\page

#{\footnote 20902}
${\footnote Visible Object Side}
+{\footnote 1}
K{\footnote Visible Object Side;}
\pard \plain \brdrb \cf12 \fs24 \b
\{bmc IDF20902.bmp\} Visible Object Side\par
\pard \plain \cf0 \fs20
{\uldb Settings}{\v 20796}\par
\par
The \b \i visible object side \i0 \b0 element is a numeric variable deciding, which object face side is supposed to be visible. To accelerate the 3D graphics painting only the front (outer) object face side is painted, the back (inner) side remaining transparent. To distinguish, which face side is the front and which the back the order of the face vertices is determining. The Peter system uses as a default value the vertices' clockwise succession. The other side of the face (counter-clockwise) is deemed to be the back one, and consequently is not painted.\par
\par
\b 0 \b0 \tab both face sides are visible\par
\b 1 \b0 \tab only front side of face is visible (clockwise)\par
\b 2 \b0 \tab only back side of face is visible (counter-clockwise)\par
\par
The default setting of the individual objects can be changed by the \b \i visible object side \i0 \b0 
element. This element is exercisable for an {\uldb active object}{\v 20810}. The setting cannot be changed globally for all objects. The default value is \b 1\b0 , which means that the face front side is visible. By setting this value to \b 2 \b0 the face back side becomes visible. This feature can be utilized e.g. when reading objects from a file, if an object uses the opposed face orientation. By setting the value equal \b 0 \b0 both face sides will become visible. This setting may be useful in objects' wire models (the {\uldb filling surfaces}{\v 20797} switch) or in non-spatial objects (as e.g. a {\uldb wall}{\v 20802}). The face back side remains lighted the same way as the face front side was lighted. For this reason the wall remains dark, if its back side is lighted.\par
\par
To light objects, \b normals \b0 are used. They are vectors that are perpendicular to the face and pointing out of the object. The normals determine how an object face will be lighted depending on the face orientation toward the light source. If the inner space of an object must be used, it is not sufficient to change only the object faces visible side. The normals remain unchanged, the object faces are lighted from the outer side and the object surface appears as if its faces were transparent, being lighted from the outer side. For this purpose it is more convenient to use the {\uldb object inversion}{\v 20800} command, which provides both the face orientation change and the normal direction change.\par
\page

