#{\footnote 20865}
${\footnote Distance of Projection Plane}
+{\footnote 1}
K{\footnote Distance of Projection Plane;}
\pard \plain \brdrb \cf12 \fs24 \b
\{bmc IDF20865.bmp\} Distance of Projection Plane\par
\pard \plain \cf0 \fs20
{\uldb Scene}{\v 20857}\par
\par
By means of the \b \i distance of projection plane \i0 \b0 element the distance of the plane can be determined on which the scene being displayed is projected. The projection plane distance specifies how large portion of the scene is supposed to be displayed. The default setting of this distance is \b 1\b0 . When the projection plane gets more distant, the cut-out of the scene displayed gets smaller. Thus a zoom scene effect (a telescope function) may be created. When the projection plane gets nearer, the cut-out of the scene displayed gets larger. Thus the fish-eye effect may be created. The projection plane distance may not be <= 0.\par
\par
For the projection plane it holds that objects the distance of which equals that of the projection plane are displayed in the unity magnitude. The unity magnitude is (3D_window_width + 3D_window_height)/2. For a square 3D window a wall sized 1x1 and lying in the projection plane will fill out exactly the entire 3D window area.\par
\par
In the 3D window objects having their minimum distance equal to 1/4 of the projection plane distance will be displayed. The maximum distance for displaying objects equals the {\uldb visual range distance}{\v 20866}.\par
\page

#{\footnote 20866}
${\footnote Visual Range Distance}
+{\footnote 1}
K{\footnote Visual Range Distance;}
\pard \plain \brdrb \cf12 \fs24 \b
\{bmc IDF20866.bmp\} Visual Range Distance\par
\pard \plain \cf0 \fs20
{\uldb Scene}{\v 20857}\par
\par
The \b \i visual range distance \i0 \b0 element defines the maximum distance in which objects are still visible. By limiting the visual range distance, thus subsequently reducing the number of objects displayed, the rendering speed (i.e. the 3D graphics painting speed) can be increased. At the same time, by diminishing the visual range distance the accuracy of the face intersection will be increased (the accuracy of the depth buffer will be increased). As a consequence, the visual range distance should be minimized. The visual range minimization is frequently combined with the {\uldb fog}{\v 20860} (distant objects vanishing in the fog or darkness), or the outlook may be restricted by the room walls. The default setting of the visual range is 100.\par
\page

#{\footnote 20856}
${\footnote Projection Type}
+{\footnote 1}
K{\footnote Projection Type;}
\pard \plain \brdrb \cf12 \fs24 \b
\{bmc IDF20856.bmp\} Projection Type\par
\pard \plain \cf0 \fs20
{\uldb Scene}{\v 20857}\par
\par
The \b \i projection type \i0 \b0 element is a numeric variable determining the mode of the scene projection onto a 3D window:\par
\par
\b \i 0 \i0 \b0 \tab perspective projection (default)\par
\b \i 1 \i0 \b0 \tab ortographic projection\par
\b \i 2 \i0 \b0 \tab perspective projection, right-handed coordinate system\par
\b \i 3 \i0 \b0 \tab ortographic projection, right-handed coordinate system\par
\par
The 0 and 1 projection types are projections of the {\uldb left-handed coordinate system}{\v 20815} (default coordinate system), the 2 and 3 projection types are projections of the right-handed coordinate system (the Z-axis pointing in the opposite direction, and the rotations having the opposite directions). The newly created objects are accommodated to the right-handed coordinate system (this does not hold for objects read from a file or a text), therefore the right-handed coordinate system should be activated before some object is created. For the right-handed coordinate system it is necessary to correct the Z coordinate of the default camera (to change it from -2 to 2), as well as to change the default lighting rotation (the Y rotation from +45 degrees to -45 degrees, the X rotation from +45 degrees to +135 degrees).\par
\par
The 0 and 2 projections are perspective projections. The object gets diminished with increasing distance. The 1 and 3 projections are orthographic projections. The object size does not depend on distance. The orthographic projection is used for engineering purposes (machine drawings, CAD programs). In the orthographic projection the scale of the scene display can be controlled by the camera scale adjustment.\par
\page

#{\footnote 20935}
${\footnote Render without Displaying}
+{\footnote 1}
K{\footnote Render without Displaying;}
\pard \plain \brdrb \cf12 \fs24 \b
\{bmc IDF20935.bmp\} Render without Displaying\par
\pard \plain \cf0 \fs20
{\uldb Scene}{\v 20857}\par
\par
The \b \i render without displaying \i0 \b0 element is a command used in special cases to render the scene without displaying on the screen. Main utilization of the command is multiple rendering e.g. when creating shadow effects behind moving objects. First rendering of the scene is usually realized with {\uldb clearing of the background}{\v 20858}. Following rendering proceeds without background clearing, objects overlap original image. Last rendering will proceed with the {\uldb wait}{\v 20122} command, with drawing on the sceen.\par
\page

